thinking:
We need to evaluate if the visualization described is misleading. The description: line chart with y-axis 0-350, compares US and Canada daily new cases per million 7-day avg. Claims US peaked 250 in April then dropped below 50 then surged to >350 by Aug 12. Canada peaked 200 in April then dropped below 20 then slight increase to <100 by Aug 12.

Potential issues: Are numbers plausible? US peak 250 per million in April 2021? Actually US cases per million around that time maybe lower. Could be okay. But note that the y-axis max is 350, but US surge goes "over 350" per million by Aug 12, but axis limited to 350 maybe truncated? It says y-axis ranging 0 to 350, but they claim US over 350. That suggests data points beyond axis limit; maybe the chart truncates the axis at 350, hiding higher values, which could be misleading (truncated axis). The description says over 350 by Aug 12, but axis max 350; if chart cuts off, the line may be cut off or exceed top, causing misinterpretation.

Also potential cherry-picking: Only showing two countries and focusing on Delta variant; but could be okay. The caption includes vaccination rates (Canada 64%, US 50%) and suggests causality. This is causal inference from correlation, possibly misleading.

The analysis says chart does not explicitly mention Delta variant or vaccination rates, which are inferred from caption. So the caption provides context linking vaccination rates to case trends. That is causal inference, maybe unsupported.

Also possibly issues with data validity: no mention of uncertainties, testing rates, etc.

But main visualization error: truncated axis (if indeed the chart cuts off at 350). The description says y-axis ranges 0 to 350. If the US line surpasses that, the chart may have truncated axis (or maybe line goes to top edge). That is misleading.

Also possible cherry-picking: only two countries, but that's a design choice, not necessarily misleading.

Thus we mark misleading: yes, due to truncated axis and causal inference (caption infers cause). Also possibly cherry-picking but less.

Now confidence: fairly high, maybe 85.

Intentionality: Likely intentional, as truncating axis to make surge appear more dramatic? Or to hide higher values? Probably intentional rhetorical design. Confidence maybe 75.

Now rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric: Yes, selection of US and Canada only, includes specific timeframe, influences narrative. So exists, confidence 90, supports misleading aspects (selection supports cherry-picking). So supports.

Provenance Rhetoric: The chart cites source Our World in Data, and caption gives vaccination rates. So provenance present, confidence 80, does not support misleading aspects (actually adds credibility). So supports_misleading false.

Mapping Rhetoric: Use of line chart mapping cases per million to position; axis truncated may affect mapping. So mapping exists, confidence 85, supports misleading (truncation manipulates perception). So true.

Linguistic-Based Rhetoric: Title, caption, and interpretation language linking vaccination to cases. Exists, confidence 85, supports misleading (causal language). So true.

Procedural Rhetoric: Not interactive, likely none. So exists false, confidence 70.

Now list error types: Truncated axis, Causal inference, Cherry-picking maybe. Also possibly Issues with data validity (lack of caveats). But main: Truncated axis, Causal inference, Cherry-picking. We'll include those.
